Brexit, and what comes next?
NEW YORK – It will take a long time for the United Kingdom, the European Union, and the world as a whole to digest the implications of the Brexit referendum led by the United Kingdom.
The deepest consequences will, of course, depend on the European Union's response to the UK's withdrawal.
Most people initially believed that the EU would not « cut the branch it was sitting on »: after all, a friendly divorce seems to be in everyone's interest.
But the divorce – as is often the case – could become complicated.
The benefits of economic and commercial integration between the United Kingdom and the EU are reciprocal, and if the EU took seriously its conviction that more economic integration is desirable, its leaders would seek to ensure that the ties remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
Yet, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive tax avoidance strategies benefiting businesses in Luxembourg and now President of the European Commission, seems to be adopting a hard line: "Out means out," he said.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be seen as the one who presided over the first stage of the EU's dissolution.
He argues that, in order to dissuade other countries from leaving, the EU must accept no compromise, offering the United Kingdom barely more than what is guaranteed by the World Trade Organization agreements.
In other words, Europe must not be kept united by the advantages it offers its members, which far exceed its costs.
The prosperity of the economy, the sense of solidarity and the pride of being European are not enough, according to Juncker.
No, Europe must be kept together by threats, intimidation and fear.
This position does not take into account a lesson that clearly appears, both in the vote in favor of Brexit and in the Republican primary elections in the United States: a large part of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the last four decades may have been good for the richest 1%, but not for the rest of the population.
I had predicted for a long time that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
This day has now arrived.
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens consider trade agreements to be the source of their miseries.
Although this is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
Today's trade agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of corporate interests but complete exclusion of ordinary citizens or workers.
As expected, the results were one-sided: workers' negotiating position has weakened further, exacerbating the effects of legislation that reduces the power of unions and workers' rights.
Although trade agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to tipping the political balance in favor of capital.
Intellectual property rules, for example, have increased the power of pharmaceutical companies to raise prices.
Yet, any increase in the market power of companies implies a de facto decline in real wages – an increase in inequalities that has become a characteristic of most advanced countries today.
In many sectors, industrial concentration is increasing – and so is market power.
The effects of stagnation and the decline in real wages have added to those of austerity, which has threatened cuts in public services that so many low- and middle-income workers depend on.
The economic uncertainty resulting for workers, when combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for all, but especially for the former colonial powers.
And yet, although many would probably deny it, an increase in the supply of unskilled labor leads – as long as we are in the presence of normal downward-sloping demand curves – to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot fall, unemployment increases.
This is especially concerning in countries where poor economic management has already led to a high level of overall unemployment.
The European Union, particularly the eurozone, has been very poorly managed over the last few decades, to the point that its average unemployment rate is now in double digits.
Unrestricted migration in Europe means that the countries that have been more successful in reducing unemployment will inevitably end up hosting more than their fair share of refugees.
The workers in these countries bear the cost of depressed wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from a cheaper labor force.
The burden of refugees, unsurprisingly, falls on those who are least able to bear it.
Of course, there is a lot of talk about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed benefits – social protection, education, healthcare, etc. – to all its citizens, this may be the case.
But, for countries that provide a decent social safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on wages and cuts in public services has been the erosion of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Households in the middle class and working class have not benefited from economic growth.
They understand that banks caused the 2008 crisis; but they then saw billions allocated to save the banks, and insignificant amounts to save their homes and jobs.
While the median real (inflation-adjusted) income for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, the anger of the electorate should come as no surprise.
Moreover, politicians who promised change have not met expectations.
Ordinary citizens knew the system was unfair, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thereby losing the little trust they still had in the ability or willingness of traditional politicians to fix it.
This is also understandable: the new politicians shared the outlook of those who had promised that globalization would be beneficial for all.
However, a vote of anger does not solve problems, and may instead lead to a political and economic situation that is even worse.
The same applies if one responds to a vote with anger.
Forgotten the past is a basic principle in economics.
On both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment could have done so little to respond to the concerns of many citizens.
Each government of the EU must now consider the improvement of the well-being of ordinary citizens as its main objective.
Davantage d’idéologie néolibérale n’aidera pas.
Et nous devrions arrêter de confondre objectifs et moyens: par exemple, le libre-échange, s’il est bien géré, pourrait apporter une plus grande prospérité partagée; mais s’il est mal géré, il réduira certainement le niveau de vie de beaucoup – peut-être de la majorité – des citoyens.
Il existe des alternatives aux dispositions néolibérales actuelles qui peuvent créer une prospérité partagée, tout comme il existe des alternatives – comme l’accord de Partenariat transatlantique de commerce et d’investissement avec l’UE proposé par le président américain Barack Obama – qui causerait beaucoup plus de mal.
Le défi aujourd'hui est d'apprendre du passé, afin d’adopter les premières et d’éviter les secondes.
